r a rez in a zone-wide channel, and invariably someone tells them to drag the corpse to where-ever they are.  I've seen this happen on a regular basis.  I have no reason to believe it'll suddenly stop. <br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Groups like to be self-sufficient. Having res handy is one of the requirements for self-sufficiency.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />Rez is nice to have.  It isn't mandatory.  And, as we all know, if a group really wants to take a rezzer along, they have 3 choices, not one.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">No one is saying resurrections should drop like candy.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />How many druids are there?  Multiply that number by the number of rezzes that will suddenly enter the game.  Thank you.  That's candy.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">People are saying that resurrections should follow suit like the rest of EQ - become available from more sources than just clerics (because frankly, pally 90% res and necro EE res just doesn't cut it; I've never seen a necro res an entire group using EE's and very few groups that depended on a pally for resses even if it meant waiting 2 hours for a cleric).<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />That's generally because they're not happy with anything but the best possible rez, and, unless druids get as good as rez as clerics, nothing will change.<br /><br />And I'll remind you that this whole debate came about not because players wanted access to more rezzes, but because druids wanted to increase their group desireability.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">That's one part of it. Risk vs. reward, of course, will always be the driving force behind why people go to a zone. All that giving resses to more classes would do is make it so that not all the people going into those zones bring along a cleric for resses, and can do without one.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />You're right, they can bring along a paladin for rezzes.  Or perhaps a necro, who has a better chance of surviving a wipe and rezzing back in the cleric/paladin who can rez everyone else.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">By the way, have you ever *tried* getting a group to go past Sebilis zone-in/necro without a cleric?<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />More than once, actually.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Have you ever tried getting five other people to go camp the myconid king without some means of ressing?<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />That mob specifically?  No.  Other places in Seb, yes.  Remember, if the shit hits the fan, everyone is dead, and the fact that you have a rezzer in your group will mean diddly-squat if he's naked on his bind point, just like you.  And if it isn't a full wipe, and the dungeon has a decent population of players, then it shouldn't take too long to find someone willing to help out.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">No, because now that group has guaranteed resses provided they can CR.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />You're assuming they have no friends to call on, no guild support, nobody else in the area willing to click them back to life.  I have a little trouble believing that.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">They won't have to sit around twiddling their thumbs begging a cleric from another zone or to possibly wait for a cleric to show up at zone-in. There is security when a cleric is around that cannot be possibly matched by any other class in the game.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />So they sit on their butt for a few minutes.  Just like they do in PoP when they wait for their corpse to pop.  Big deal.  Yes, it's nice to have a cleric along.  We all know that.  But clerics are not the only ones who can rez.  Paladins can, too.  And if you discount paladin rez, you invalidate any potential druid rez that isn't as good as a cleric's.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Since we've elimated travel time, and we've Since we've eliminated travel time and the "risk" of corpse loss, the game has become more convenient and, as some would say, casual-friendly. Sure, some people would prefer that we never got rid of either (like myself), but *since* we've gotten rid of the frustration inherent in both, why not go the next step and eliminate the frustration in ressing, too?<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />Because at the point the game becomes too easy, it becomes a joke.  That's why.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">It's not logical to get rid of two facets in EQ that made death frustrating and then leave the third in.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />The faster you get back to your corpse, the sooner you can get it rezzed.  It's as simple as that.  The reductions to travel time and the introduction of graveyards have pretty-much made it unnecessary to increase the number of rezzing classes.  You, or a friendly cleric, can get their in very short order.  End of problem.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Sure, to you it might seem like it's the last bastion of hope for "risk" in the game, but to me it just seems special preference to clerics because they'd be unbalanced otherwise (or so the clerics claim). Hey, we've gotten rid of the need for wizard/druid ports with PoK, and necros/SKs with GY's, but we're not going to make ressing any easier because...?<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />Because it's not necessary.  It won't make druids anymore welcome in groups than they already are (and they already are).  And it will make a powerful soloing class even more powerful.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">And I've already refuted your claim that ressing has in itself any risk element. Perhaps you would choose to believe otherwise, which is fine and dandy, but let me tell you this: I was more afraid to die in DAOC for the duration of time that I played that game than I am right now in EQ, because I know there's *always* a way to get a res here and lose nothing at all, whereas in DAOC it was a straight up loss every time.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />That's right.  DAoC where you can run back to your gravestone and pray to get back a large chunk of your lost experience, and then go train back any lost Con.  Okay, you might lose a little on the deal, but it's the same with EQ.<br /><br />But thank you for agreeing my point that "there's *always* a way to get a res here and lose nothing at all" (except that little 4%).  Now, if you would just realize that this means that druids don't need rez.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">The only difference here is the frustration factor, which doesn't help me enjoy the game.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />Any game that includes any sort of setback will have a certain level of frustration, and it's impossible to remove it.  I'm afraid you're just going to have to live with frustration, from time to time.  Life is like that.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">I would never realistically consider necros a ressing class except for in raid-wiping situations, and paladins, with their 90% resses, simply doesn't cut it because people are much more protective of their exp bar than they ever are of their mana-regen or slow percentage.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />Which means that if druid rez is not the exact same as cleric rez, then druid rez will not be desired.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Of course, even if we considered paladins a res class, that's still only two classes out of fourteen. The abilities that I can think off of the top of my head that were shared by only two classes are corpse summoning (SKs + Necros) and porting (wizards + druids), and they're both trivialized now, so...<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />Ok, here's some.<br /><br />Crowd control.  Yes, a couple other classes can do a so-so job of it, but if you want good crowd control, you get an enchanter.  Period.<br /><br />Slow.  This is a biggie.  Yes, enchanters can do it, but if they're on crowd control, they're probably too busy to do it, not to mention the risk factor of doing both at once.  So you're going to want a shaman or a beast lord to do that, unless you want to rely on a weapon proc (I wouldn't advise it), or perhaps if you're fighting undead, at which point necros are actually able to help.  But, no...if you want slow, and you're going to want slow, then you're going to go for a shaman or a beastlord.<br /><br />Evac.  Not port.  Evac.  We're talking dungeons, so you're probably going to want someone who can evac you to the zone's safe spot when the shit hits the fan, like it sometimes does in dungeons.  Two classes can do this, one of them druids.<br /><br />There, that's two or three very important roles that are locked-down by a very limited number of classes.  Which one of those monopolies will we break, next?<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Regardless, if you choose to believe that people will go without clerics into the Lost Dungeons of Norrath (which is the entire point of making resses more available), then I applaud your optimism. I consider myself more realistic.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />Considering how much we don't know about these dungeons, it's pretty damn early to be making predictions about what we'll need.  If they follow the PoP and LoY model of having graveyards, then it'll make getting rezzes all the easier.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">To me, this entire discussion has been about the nature of risk. I argue that risk cannot exist when one class trivializes it and thus merely becomes frustration. You argue, it seems to me, that there is still risk left in the game in the form of deaths, but only for groups that do not have clerics. It seems to me then that the obvious solution would be to get clerics, which turns out to be the whole problem in the first place.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />No, I don't see there being much risk at all.  It's easy to get rezzes now, by your own admission.  I doubt it'll get any harder.  My argument is that it isn't necessary to give any other class access to rez, because it's already usually easy to get one.<br /><br />You are entitled to your own opinion, of course, but I don't happen to agree with it.</span></font></td>
