                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;06/16/2003&nbsp;: 01:05:23 AM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">That's their problem. Should we hand them the game on a silver platter, too?<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />That is the game's problem.  If I was a developer, would I create tough zones that bring back the concept of danger and risk if 95% of the player population won't visit them? Saying that it's the players fault' doesn't work and is illogical, because there was a time in EQ when people actually went to dungeons.  The reason they're not going anymore is purely a design problem.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">There is no requirement to bring along any class that has a cleric, or person who can rez, because there is nearly always one nearby who can do it.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Yeah, because groups just *love* to bother that cleric nearby who is in another group and already pressed for mana healing them, right? Because that cleric will *always* res you, right, and won't ever say that they're busy? <br /><br />Groups like to be self-sufficient.  Having res handy is one of the requirements for self-sufficiency.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">At the point where resurrections drop like candy, you have, in fact, trivialized death. And giving rez to more classes does just that. <hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />No one is saying resurrections should drop like candy.  People are saying that resurrections should follow suit like the rest of EQ - become available from more sources than just clerics (because frankly, pally 90% res and necro EE res just doesn't cut it; I've never seen a necro res an entire group using EE's and very few groups that depended on a pally for resses even if it meant waiting 2 hours for a cleric).<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">That won't change. People will go to the new dungeons for the loot, and they'll go there if it's good experience. Just like Sebilis. There will likely be plenty of people to call on if the need arises. If there aren't, it's because the loot is lacking, and/or the xp sucks.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />That's one part of it.  Risk vs. reward, of course, will always be the driving force behind why people go to a zone.  All that giving resses to more classes would do is make it so that not all the people going into those zones bring along a cleric for resses, and can do without one.  <br /><br />By the way, have you ever *tried* getting a group to go past Sebilis zone-in/necro without a cleric? Have you ever tried getting five other people to go camp the myconid king without some means of ressing?<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">And if the group wipes, having a cleric who can rez will do them absolutely no good, and we're back to square one.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />No, because now that group has guaranteed resses provided they can CR.  They won't have to sit around twiddling their thumbs begging a cleric from another zone or to possibly wait for a cleric to show up at zone-in.  There is security when a cleric is around that cannot be possibly matched by any other class in the game.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Since we've elimated travel time, and we've eliminated risk of corpse loss, shall we also completely trivialize death itself? At that rate, why don't we just go play DAoC where you respawn with all your gear, and the rez is gravy?<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Since we've eliminated travel time and the "risk" of corpse loss, the game has become more convenient and, as some would say, casual-friendly.  Sure, some people would prefer that we never got rid of either (like myself), but *since* we've gotten rid of the frustration inherent in both, why not go the next step and eliminate the frustration in ressing, too?<br /><br />It's not logical to get rid of two facets in EQ that made death frustrating and then leave the third in.  Sure, to you it might seem like it's the last bastion of hope for "risk" in the game, but to me it just seems special preference to clerics because they'd be unbalanced otherwise (or so the clerics claim).  Hey, we've gotten rid of the need for wizard/druid ports with PoK, and necros/SKs with GY's, but we're not going to make ressing any easier because...?<br /><br />And I've already refuted your claim that ressing has in itself any risk element.  Perhaps you would choose to believe otherwise, which is fine and dandy, but let me tell you this: I was more afraid to die in DAOC for the duration of time that I played that game than I am right now in EQ, because I know there's *always* a way to get a res here and lose nothing at all, whereas in DAOC it was a straight up loss every time.  The only difference here is the frustration factor, which doesn't help me enjoy the game.<br />  <br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">And, as a reminder, resurrection is not an ability that a single class has a monopoly on. Three classes can rez, including us.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />I would never realistically consider necros a ressing class except for in raid-wiping situations, and paladins, with their 90% resses, simply doesn't cut it because people are much more protective of their exp bar than they ever are of their mana-regen or slow percentage.<br /><br />Of course, even if we considered paladins a res class, that's still only two classes out of fourteen.  The abilities that I can think off of the top of my head that were shared by only two classes are corpse summoning (SKs + Necros) and porting (wizards + druids), and they're both trivialized now, so...<br /><br />Regardless, if you choose to believe that people will go without clerics into the Lost Dungeons of Norrath (which is the entire point of making resses more available), then I applaud your optimism.  I consider myself more realistic.<br /><br />To me, this entire discussion has been about the nature of risk.  I argue that risk cannot exist when one class trivializes it and thus merely becomes frustration.  You argue, it seems to me, that there is still risk left in the game in the form of deaths, but only for groups that do not have clerics.  It seems to me then that the obvious solution would be to get clerics, which turns out to be the whole problem in the first place.<br /><br /></span></font></td>
